# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: games-behind
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:games-behind/1972-detroit-tigers-season] The **1972 Detroit Tigers season** was the team's 72nd season and the 61st season at Tiger Stadium.
[src:games-behind/1972-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers won the American League East championship with a record of 86–70 (.551), finishing one-half game ahead of the Boston Red Sox.
[src:games-behind/1972-detroit-tigers-season] They played one more game than the Red Sox due to a scheduling quirk caused by the 1972 Major League Baseball strike—a game which turned out to allow them to win the division.
[src:games-behind/1972-detroit-tigers-season] They lost the 1972 American League Championship Series to the Oakland A's three games to two.
[src:games-behind/1972-detroit-tigers-season] Mickey Lolich recorded 376 innings pitched (IP), surpassing Bob Feller's 1946 live-ball era record of 371+1⁄3.
[src:games-behind/1972-detroit-tigers-season] The following season, Wilbur Wood of the Chicago White Sox set a new record with 376+2⁄3 IP.
[src:games-behind/1972-detroit-tigers-season] After having a losing record in 1970, the Tigers were reinvigorated in 1971 and 1972 by their fiery manager, Billy Martin.
[src:games-behind/1972-detroit-tigers-season] The 1972 Tigers were an aging team whose best hitters (Al Kaline and Norm Cash) were both 37 years old.
[src:games-behind/1972-detroit-tigers-season] Together with the late-season acquisition of 38-year-old slugger Frank Howard, this led to a group of Tigers batters who were past their prime, and the team finished the year with an anemic .237 batting average—seventh in the AL.
[src:games-behind/1972-detroit-tigers-season] Light-hitting third baseman Aurelio Rodríguez led the team with 142 hits, and the 37-year-olds Kaline and Cash led the way in batting average (Kaline hit .313), RBIs (Cash had 61), and home runs (Cash had 22).
[src:games-behind/1972-detroit-tigers-season] The strength of the 1972 team was pitching.
[src:games-behind/1972-detroit-tigers-season] The team's ace, Mickey Lolich, won 22 games, struck out 250 batters (2nd best in the AL), and had a 2.50 ERA.
[src:games-behind/1972-detroit-tigers-season] Joe Coleman had 19 wins and 222 strikeouts, and the early August acquisition of Woodie Fryman proved to be a key element in a tight pennant race.
[src:games-behind/1972-detroit-tigers-season] Between August 1 and 17, the Tigers went 5–12, and three of the team's wins were by Fryman.
[src:games-behind/1972-detroit-tigers-season] Excluding Fryman's wins, the Tigers were 2–12 in the first half of August.
[src:games-behind/1972-detroit-tigers-season] In the final two months of the season, Fryman had a 10–3 record with a 2.06 ERA (Adjusted ERA+ of 154).
[src:games-behind/1972-detroit-tigers-season] Defense also played an important role in the team's success.
[src:games-behind/1972-detroit-tigers-season] Rodríguez led AL third basemen with 150 putouts and 348 assists, and shortstop Ed Brinkman won the Gold Glove award and led AL shortstops with a .990 fielding percentage (33 points above the league average).
[src:games-behind/1972-detroit-tigers-season] Brinkman set a record going 72 games and 331 total chances without an error from late May through early August.
[src:games-behind/1972-detroit-tigers-season] Despite a .205 batting average, Brinkman won the "Tiger of the Year" award from the Detroit baseball writers and finished ninth in the American League MVP voting.
[src:games-behind/1972-detroit-tigers-season] The 1972 Tigers outscored their opponents 558 to 514.
[src:games-behind/1972-detroit-tigers-season] The pennant race came down to the final series, a matchup between the first place Red Sox and the second place Tigers.
[src:games-behind/1972-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers won two of three games and finished a half game ahead of the Red Sox.
[src:games-behind/1972-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit's attendance total of 1,892,386 was tops among the twelve American League teams and second in the majors behind the New York Mets.
[src:games-behind/1972-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers lost to the Oakland Athletics in the 1972 American League Championship Series, losing three games to two.
[src:games-behind/1972-detroit-tigers-season] The A's were 93–62 in the regular season and went on to beat the Cincinnati Reds in the 1972 World Series.
[src:games-behind/1972-detroit-tigers-season] The Series moved to Detroit for the final three games.
[src:games-behind/1972-detroit-tigers-season] In **Game 3**, Joe Coleman (19–14) pitched a complete-game shutout and set an ALCS record by striking out 14 A's batters.
[src:games-behind/1972-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers won, 3–0, as Ike Brown hit a single in the 4th inning that drove in Al Kaline and Bill Freehan.
[src:games-behind/1972-detroit-tigers-season] Freehan also hit a home run in the 8th inning to complete the scoring.
[src:games-behind/1972-detroit-tigers-season] Ken Holtzman (19–11) was the losing pitcher for the A's.
[src:games-behind/1972-detroit-tigers-season] The decisive **Game 5** was another pitching duel between Blue Moon Odom and Woodie Fryman.
[src:games-behind/1972-detroit-tigers-season] Both teams combined for only nine hits, and the only extra-base hit was a double by Odom.
[src:games-behind/1972-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers scored first in the bottom of the first inning, as Dick McAuliffe singled, moved to second on a walk, moved to third on a passed ball, and scored on a groundball by Bill Freehan.
[src:games-behind/1972-detroit-tigers-season] The A's tied in the top of the second inning, as Reggie Jackson walked, stole second base, advanced to third on a fly ball, and then stole home.
[src:games-behind/1972-detroit-tigers-season] In the fourth inning, George Hendrick reached base on a controversial throwing error (umpire John Rice ruled that first baseman Norm Cash had pulled his foot off the bag but replays showed otherwise).
[src:games-behind/1972-detroit-tigers-season] He advanced to second on a bunt, and scored on a Gene Tenace single to left field.
[src:games-behind/1972-detroit-tigers-season] Neither team scored a run after the top of the fourth, and the A's won the game, 2–1.
[src:games-behind/1972-detroit-tigers-season] In the 9th inning, Norm Cash singled, but pinch hitter Mickey Stanley hit into a fielder's choice and Tony Taylor hit a fly ball to center for the final out.
[src:games-behind/1972-detroit-tigers-season] Odom and Vida Blue combined to hold the Tigers to five hits.
[src:games-behind/1972-detroit-tigers-season] Despite allowing only one earned run, Fryman took the loss.
[src:games-behind/1990-nfl-season] The **1990 NFL season** was the 71st regular season of the National Football League (NFL).
[src:games-behind/1990-nfl-season] To increase revenue, the league, for the first time since 1966, reinstated bye weeks, so that all NFL teams would play their 16-game schedule over a 17-week period.
[src:games-behind/1990-nfl-season] Ironically, the first sixth-seeded playoff team would not have a 10–6 record, but instead, the New Orleans Saints, with an 8–8 record, took the new playoff spot.
[src:games-behind/1990-nfl-season] The season ended with Super Bowl XXV when the New York Giants defeated the Buffalo Bills 20–19 at Tampa Stadium.
[src:games-behind/1990-nfl-season] This would be the first Super Bowl appearance for Buffalo, who would represent the AFC in the next three Super Bowls as well.
[src:games-behind/1990-nfl-season] This was the first full season for Paul Tagliabue as the league's Commissioner, after taking over from Pete Rozelle midway through the previous season.
[src:games-behind/1990-nfl-season] On October 8, the league announced that the Super Bowl Most Valuable Player Award would be named the Pete Rozelle Trophy in the former commissioner's honor.
[src:games-behind/1990-nfl-season] The 1990 NFL draft was held from April 22 to 23, 1990, at New York City's Marriott Marquis.
[src:games-behind/1990-nfl-season] With the first pick, the Indianapolis Colts selected quarterback Jeff George from the University of Illinois.
[src:games-behind/1990-nfl-season] Selecting seventeenth overall, the Dallas Cowboys would draft Emmitt Smith, who would retire as the NFL's all-time leading rusher.
[src:games-behind/1990-nfl-season] Dick Jorgensen, who had been the referee in the previous season's Super Bowl XXIV, was diagnosed in May during the offseason with a rare blood disorder.
[src:games-behind/1990-nfl-season] He died five months later on October 10.
[src:games-behind/1990-nfl-season] For the remainder of the 1990 season, NFL officials wore a black armband on their left sleeve with the white number 60 to honor Jorgensen.
[src:games-behind/1990-nfl-season] Ben Dreith (a referee in the AFL from 1966 to 1969, and the NFL since the merger) and Fred Wyant (a referee since 1971), were demoted to line judge.
[src:games-behind/1990-nfl-season] Dreith later filed a complaint to the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission after the league fired him after the 1990 season, citing age discrimination as the reason for both his demotion to line judge and his dismissal.
[src:games-behind/1990-nfl-season] Dreith and the NFL would later agree in 1993 to a $165,000 settlement, plus court costs and attorney fees.
[src:games-behind/1990-nfl-season] Gerald Austin, the side judge for Super Bowl XXIV, and Tom White, were promoted to referee.
[src:games-behind/1990-nfl-season] White became the first official to be promoted to referee after only one season of NFL experience since Jerry Markbreit in 1977 (Tommy Bell (1962) and Brad Allen (2014) were hired straight into the NFL as referees).
[src:games-behind/1990-nfl-season] After one season with having 16 officiating crews in 1989, it was reduced back to 15 crews in 1990 to handle the weekly workload of 14 games (if there were no teams with a bye week).
[src:games-behind/1990-nfl-season] Ed Hochuli was hired as a back judge (now field judge) and assigned to Howard Roe's crew.
[src:games-behind/1990-nfl-season] Hochuli was promoted to referee two years later.
[src:games-behind/1990-nfl-season] A series of National Football League pre-season exhibition games that were held at sites outside the United States, a total of four games were held in 1990.
[src:games-behind/1990-nfl-season] With New England Patriots founder Billy Sullivan no longer owning the team, having it sold to Victor Kiam in 1988 and Sullivan Stadium being taken over by Robert Kraft, the venue was renamed Foxboro Stadium.
[src:games-behind/1990-nfl-season] In Week 16 with the Gulf War looming closer, American flag decals were added to the back of the helmets of all players.
[src:games-behind/1990-nfl-season] This was the first season under a new four-year deal with TNT to televise Sunday night football games during the first half of the season.
[src:games-behind/1990-nfl-season] ABC, CBS, NBC, and ESPN also each signed four-year contracts to renew their rights for *Monday Night Football*, the NFC package, and the AFC package, and *Sunday Night Football* during the second half of the season, respectively.
[src:games-behind/1990-nfl-season] ABC was also given the rights to televise the additional Saturday AFC and NFC wild card playoff games.
[src:games-behind/1990-nfl-season] TNT's initial broadcast team consisted of Skip Caray on play-by-play and Pat Haden as color commentator.
[src:games-behind/1990-nfl-season] Fred Hickman became the host of TNT's pregame show, *The Stadium Show*.
[src:games-behind/1990-nfl-season] ESPN continued to air *NFL Primetime* during those Sunday nights when TNT aired games, going head-to-head with TNT's pregame show.
[src:games-behind/1990-nfl-season] After CBS fired Brent Musburger on April 1, 1990, the network decided to overhaul the talent lineup on *The NFL Today*.
[src:games-behind/1990-nfl-season] Irv Cross was demoted to the position of game analyst, Dick Butkus returned to acting, and Will McDonough moved on to NBC's *NFL Live!*.
[src:games-behind/1990-nfl-season] Greg Gumbel became the new host of *The NFL Today*.
[src:games-behind/1990-nfl-season] Terry Bradshaw became the new analyst, while Pat O'Brien, Lesley Visser, and Jim Gray as the new reporters/contributors.
[src:games-behind/1990-nfl-season] Late in the 1990 season, Pat Summerall was hospitalized with a bleeding ulcer after vomiting on a plane following his calling a Chicago Bears-Washington Redskins game and would not return to the booth until the 1990 NFC Divisional Playoff Game between the Bears and New York Giants.
[src:games-behind/1990-nfl-season] In Summerall's absence, CBS teamed John Madden with Dick Stockton for one week before teaming him with Verne Lundquist until Summerall was well enough to work, while Jack Buck, the lead voice of NFL coverage on CBS Radio and CBS' Major League Baseball coverage, was added as a fill-in broadcaster.
[src:games-behind/1994-atlanta-braves-season] The **1994 Atlanta Braves season** was the Braves' 124th in existence and their 29th in Atlanta.
[src:games-behind/1994-atlanta-braves-season] After trading the two-sport athlete Deion Sanders, experts predicted that the Atlanta Braves were going to have their worst season since 1935.
[src:games-behind/1994-atlanta-braves-season] The Braves' records reflect just how successful that year was, although it was curtailed due to the 1994–95 Major League Baseball strike.
[src:games-behind/1994-atlanta-braves-season] The Braves played a total of 114 games; they won 68 and lost 46.
[src:games-behind/1994-atlanta-braves-season] The Braves finished their 1994 season with a winning percentage of .596, ranking the Braves third overall in MLB, although they were six games behind the Montreal Expos in the NL East.
[src:games-behind/1994-atlanta-braves-season] By Friday, August 12, the Braves had compiled a 68–46 record through 114 games.
[src:games-behind/1994-atlanta-braves-season] They were leading the 1994 NL Wildcard Race over the Houston Astros by 2.5 games.
[src:games-behind/1994-atlanta-braves-season] The Braves had scored 542 runs (4.75 per game) and allowed 448 runs (3.93 per game).
[src:games-behind/1994-atlanta-braves-season] Braves' pitching was perhaps the best in the Majors in 1994: they gave up only 76 home runs in 114 games, the fewest home runs allowed among all 28 teams and they allowed only 929 hits, also the fewest among all 28 teams.
[src:games-behind/1994-atlanta-braves-season] Furthermore, they led the MLB in most strikeouts (865) and allowed the fewest runs (448) and earned runs (407).
[src:games-behind/1994-atlanta-braves-season] May 29, 1994: Deion Sanders was traded by the Atlanta Braves to the Cincinnati Reds for Roberto Kelly and Roger Etheridge (minors).
[src:games-behind/1994-florida-marlins-season] The **1994 Florida Marlins season** was the second season for the Major League Baseball (MLB) franchise in the National League.
[src:games-behind/1994-florida-marlins-season] It would begin with the team attempting to improve on their season from 1993.
[src:games-behind/1994-florida-marlins-season] They played home games at Joe Robbie Stadium.
[src:games-behind/1994-florida-marlins-season] They finished with a record of 51–64, last in the National League East.
[src:games-behind/1994-florida-marlins-season] The season ended early as a result of the 1994 players strike.
[src:games-behind/1994-florida-marlins-season] By Friday, August 12, the Marlins had compiled a 51-64 record through 115 games.
[src:games-behind/1994-florida-marlins-season] They had scored 468 runs (4.07 per game) and allowed 576 runs (5.01 per game).
[src:games-behind/1994-florida-marlins-season] Charlie Hough was 46 when he took the hill on Opening Day for the Marlins.
[src:games-behind/1994-florida-marlins-season] He was the second oldest pitcher to pitch on opening day.
[src:games-behind/1994-florida-marlins-season] Jack Quinn started for the Brooklyn Dodgers on Opening Day in 1931 at the age of 47.
[src:games-behind/1994-major-league-baseball-season] The **1994 Major League Baseball season** began on April 3, but ended prematurely on August 11, 1994, with the 1994–95 Major League Baseball strike.
[src:games-behind/1994-major-league-baseball-season] The season started despite the expiration of MLB's previous collective bargaining agreement at the end of 1993.
[src:games-behind/1994-major-league-baseball-season] It was the first season played under the current three-division format in each league.
[src:games-behind/1994-major-league-baseball-season] It was also the first with an Opening Night game involving two National League teams, which did not become permanent until 1996.
[src:games-behind/1994-major-league-baseball-season] As a result of a players' strike, the MLB season ended prematurely on August 11, 1994.
[src:games-behind/1994-major-league-baseball-season] No postseason (including the World Series) was played.
[src:games-behind/1994-major-league-baseball-season] Over 260 players were scheduled to exceed $1 million in compensation in 1994.
[src:games-behind/1994-major-league-baseball-season] The Minor League Baseball season was played in its entirety.
[src:games-behind/1994-major-league-baseball-season] MLB Baseball would not attempt another salary cap until 2026.
[src:games-behind/1994-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season of The Baseball Network, the joint venture between MLB, ABC, and NBC.
[src:games-behind/1994-major-league-baseball-season] Meanwhile, ESPN renewed its contract for *Sunday Night Baseball* and *Wednesday Night Baseball*.
[src:games-behind/1994-major-league-baseball-season] Under The Baseball Network's original plan, the All-Star Game would alternate between NBC in even-numbered years and ABC in odd-numbered years.
[src:games-behind/1994-major-league-baseball-season] After the All-Star Game was complete, ABC took over coverage with what was to be their weekly slate of games under the *Baseball Night in America* banner.
[src:games-behind/1994-major-league-baseball-season] ABC was scheduled to televise six regular season games on Saturdays or Mondays in prime time.
[src:games-behind/1994-major-league-baseball-season] NBC would then pick up where ABC left off by televising six more regular season Friday night games.
[src:games-behind/1994-major-league-baseball-season] Every *Baseball Night in America* game was scheduled to begin at 8 p.m.
[src:games-behind/1994-major-league-baseball-season] Pacific Time if the game occurred on the West Coast).
[src:games-behind/1994-major-league-baseball-season] A single starting time gave the networks the opportunity to broadcast one game and then, simultaneously, cut to another game when there was a break in action.
[src:games-behind/1994-major-league-baseball-season] The networks had exclusive rights for the twelve regular season dates, in that no regional or national cable service (such as ESPN or superstations like Chicago's WGN-TV or Atlanta's WTBS) or over-the-air broadcaster was allowed to telecast a Major League Baseball game on those dates.
[src:games-behind/1994-major-league-baseball-season] *Baseball Night in America* (which premiered on July 16, 1994) usually aired up to fourteen games based on the viewers' region (affiliates chose games of local interest to carry) as opposed to a traditional coast-to-coast format.
[src:games-behind/1994-major-league-baseball-season] Normally, announcers who represented each of the teams playing in the respective games were paired with each other.
[src:games-behind/1994-major-league-baseball-season] More specifically, on regional Saturday night broadcasts and all non-"national" broadcasts, TBN let the two lead announcers from the opposing teams call the games involving their teams together.
[src:games-behind/1994-major-league-baseball-season] Postseason coverage would have also alternated between the two networks.
[src:games-behind/1994-major-league-baseball-season] In even-numbered years, NBC would have the rights to the All-Star Game and both League Championship Series while ABC would have the World Series and newly created Division Series.
[src:games-behind/1994-major-league-baseball-season] When the player's strike began on August 12, ABC had only aired games on four of its six scheduled dates, while NBC's slate was supposed to begin on August 26.
[src:games-behind/1994-montreal-expos-season] The 1994 Montreal Expos season was the 26th season of the franchise.
[src:games-behind/1994-montreal-expos-season] They had the best record in Major League Baseball (74–40), when the 1994–95 Major League Baseball strike ended the season and the team's postseason aspirations.
[src:games-behind/1994-montreal-expos-season] From June 1 forward, Montreal transformed into the dominant club in the league, going 46−18 until the strike.
[src:games-behind/1994-montreal-expos-season] In turn, they also produced the most successful season in franchise history in terms of winning percentage (.649, which would have been 105–57 in a full season).
[src:games-behind/1994-montreal-expos-season] Five Expos represented the National League at the All-Star Game held in Pittsburgh, including Moisés Alou, who had the game-winning hit for the National League.
[src:games-behind/1994-montreal-expos-season] The Expos held spring training at West Palm Beach Municipal Stadium in West Palm Beach, Florida – a facility they shared with the Atlanta Braves.
[src:games-behind/1994-montreal-expos-season] It was their 18th season at the stadium; they had conducted spring training there from 1969 to 1972 and since 1981.
[src:games-behind/1994-montreal-expos-season] On April 13, 1994, Pedro Martínez took a perfect game through 71⁄3 innings versus the Cincinnati Reds until throwing a brushback pitch at Reggie Sanders led Sanders to immediately charge the mound, starting a bench-clearing brawl.
[src:games-behind/1994-montreal-expos-season] Martínez ended up with a no-decision in the game, which the Expos eventually won 3–2.
[src:games-behind/1994-montreal-expos-season] One amusing moment occurred on April 24 while playing the Dodgers at Dodger Stadium in Los Angeles.
[src:games-behind/1994-montreal-expos-season] With one out in the third inning, right fielder Larry Walker caught a Mike Piazza fly ball and innocently handed it to young fan, six year old Sebastian Napier, thinking it was the third out of the inning.
[src:games-behind/1994-montreal-expos-season] He noticed that José Offerman, already on base, was running at full speed.
[src:games-behind/1994-montreal-expos-season] Walker managed to retrieve the ball from Napier, and held Offerman to third base.
[src:games-behind/1994-montreal-expos-season] Embarrassed, Walker remarked that he "told the little kid that maybe next time I'll give him a ball when there are three outs instead of two.
[src:games-behind/1994-montreal-expos-season] Everybody around him was laughing." Where Offerman was stationed made little difference as Tim Wallach homered on the next pitch, from Martínez, for two runs.
[src:games-behind/1994-montreal-expos-season] True to his word, when the Expos assumed the field in the bottom half of the fourth inning, Walker gave Napier a signed ball, inducing a standing ovation.
[src:games-behind/1994-montreal-expos-season] The National League suspended Walker four games starting June 24 for inciting a bench-clearing brawl by charging the mound in a game against Pittsburgh.
[src:games-behind/1994-montreal-expos-season] The Expos team appeared to be reaching its potential in 1994.
[src:games-behind/1994-montreal-expos-season] After June 1, Montreal transformed into the dominant club in the National League, going 46−18 until the players' strike halted the season on August 11.
[src:games-behind/1994-montreal-expos-season] Led by an ensemble of rising young stars including Martínez, Walker, Moisés Alou, Cliff Floyd, Mike Lansing and Jeff Fassero, the Expos scored 585 runs (5.13 per game) and allowed 454 runs (3.98 per game) through 114 games by Friday, August 12.
[src:games-behind/1994-montreal-expos-season] Their 1994 pitching staff was very nearly as good as that of their division rivals, the Atlanta Braves, as the Expos finished the strike-shortened season with an MLB-best 3.56 ERA, an MLB-high 46 saves and just 288 walks, the fewest in the Majors.
[src:games-behind/1994-montreal-expos-season] Walker, with 86 RBIs, was well on his way to his first 100-RBI year; Ken Hill was on pace to win 23 games while Pedro Martínez was on pace to strike out more than 200 batters.
[src:games-behind/1994-montreal-expos-season] Moisés Alou was hitting .339 and on pace to collect more than 200 hits for the first time in his career.
[src:games-behind/1994-montreal-expos-season] Marquis Grissom was on pace to score 137 runs.
[src:games-behind/1994-montreal-expos-season] Two other Expos, namely Alou and Walker, were also on pace to score more than 100 runs.
[src:games-behind/1994-montreal-expos-season] The team was also drawing well at home: through 52 home games in 1994, 1,276,250 fans had attended Expos games, for an average of 24,543 per game.
[src:games-behind/1994-montreal-expos-season] At that pace, the Expos would have had a good chance of drawing two million fans for the first time since 1983.
[src:games-behind/1994-montreal-expos-season] The season, however, was stopped due to the 1994 players' strike.
[src:games-behind/1994-montreal-expos-season] The World Series, for which the Expos appeared to be destined, was never played and Montreal lost many of its players during the next season due to free agency and salary constraints and the team never recovered.
[src:games-behind/1994-montreal-expos-season] The 1994 Montreal Expos team that could have been remains one of baseball's hot discussion points.
[src:games-behind/1994-montreal-expos-season] The franchise would never reach the playoffs as the Expos again.
[src:games-behind/1994-montreal-expos-season] The collapse of the Expos would eventually lead to the franchise's move to Washington, D.C., for the 2005 season to become the Washington Nationals.
[src:games-behind/1994-montreal-expos-season] When baseball returned for an exhibition series in Olympic Stadium in March 2014, the team was honored during a pregame ceremony, along with a banner with the words *On se souvient Édition 1994* (We remember the 1994 season).
[src:games-behind/1994-new-york-mets-season] The **1994 New York Mets season** was the 33rd attempt at a regular season for the Mets.
[src:games-behind/1994-new-york-mets-season] They went 55–58 and finished third in the National League East, eighteen and a half games behind the first place Montreal Expos.
[src:games-behind/1994-new-york-mets-season] The season was cut short by the 1994 player's strike.
[src:games-behind/1994-new-york-mets-season] By Friday, August 12, the Mets had compiled a 55–58 record through 113 games.
[src:games-behind/1994-new-york-mets-season] They had scored 521 runs (4.48 per game) and allowed 526 runs (4.65 per game).
[src:games-behind/1994-new-york-mets-season] The Mets struggled in a few offensive areas, finishing 28th in the Majors in both stolen bases (25) and on-base percentage (.316).
[src:games-behind/1994-new-york-mets-season] In spite of these numbers, the Mets had good power, slamming 117 home runs in 113 games, while grounding into just 70 double plays (the fewest in the Majors) and being hit by pitches an MLB-high 52 times.
[src:games-behind/1994-new-york-mets-season] Jeff Kent's .292 average led the team, as did his 68 RBI.
[src:games-behind/1994-new-york-mets-season] Bobby Bonilla led five Mets with double-digit home run totals with 20.
[src:games-behind/1994-new-york-mets-season] Ryan Thompson added 18, Todd Hundley 16, Kent 14, and David Segui 10.
[src:games-behind/1994-new-york-mets-season] After two injury-filled and disappointing years, Bret Saberhagen emerged as the ace of the Mets' staff with a 14–4 record.
[src:games-behind/1994-new-york-mets-season] Bobby Jones recorded 12 wins in his first full season in the rotation, and John Franco stayed healthy enough to record 30 saves.
[src:games-behind/1994-new-york-mets-season] After struggling in his first seven starts, Dwight Gooden was suspended for 60 days after a positive test for cocaine.
[src:games-behind/1994-new-york-mets-season] While on suspension he tested positive again and the suspension was extended to the entire 1995 season.
[src:games-behind/1994-new-york-mets-season] Thus, 1994 was his final season as a Met.
[src:games-behind/games-behind] In some North American sports, the phrase **games behind** or **games back** (often abbreviated **GB**) refers to a common way to reflect the gap between a leading team and another team in a sports league, conference, or division.
[src:games-behind/games-behind] In the standings below from the 1994 Major League Baseball season, the Atlanta Braves are six *games behind* the Montreal Expos.
[src:games-behind/games-behind] Atlanta would have to win six games, and Montreal would have to lose six games, to tie for first.
[src:games-behind/games-behind] The leading team is by definition zero games behind itself, and this is indicated in the standings with a dash, not a zero.
[src:games-behind/games-behind] Games behind is calculated by using either of the following formulas, in which Team A is a leading team, and Team B is a trailing team.
